5","1135":"1135","1179":"1179","1200":"1200","1155":"1155","about 1179":"okolo 1179","about 1175":"okolo 1175","Malpas, Cheshire, England":"Malpas, Cheshire, Anglie"},"da":{"about 1150–":"omkring 1150–Afdød","1150–Female":"1150–Afdød","1150–Male":"1150–Afdød","1154–Male":"1154–Afdød","1155–Female":"1155–Afdød","1160–Female":"1160–Afdød","1140–1181":"1140–1181","1170–1217":"1170–1217","1175–Male":"1175–Afdød","1179–Male":"1179–Afdød","1125–1200":"1125–1200","1135–1175":"1135–1175","about 1150":"omkring 1150","1154":"1154","1175":"1175","1140":"1140","1150":"1150","1160":"1160","1170":"1170","1181":"1181","1217":"1217","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1125":"1125","1135":"1135","1179":"1179","1200":"1200","1155":"1155","about 1179":"omkring 1179","about 1175":"omkring 1175","Malpas, Cheshire, England":"Malpas, Cheshire, England"},"nl":{"about 1150–":"circa 1150–Overleden","1150–Female":"1150–Overleden","1150–Male":"1150–Overleden","1154–Male":"1154–Overleden","1155–Female":"1155–Overleden","1160–Female":"1160–Overleden","1140–1181":"1140–1181","1170–1217":"1170–1217","1175–Male":"1175–Overleden","1179–Male":"1179–Overleden","1125–1200":"1125–1200","1135–1175":"1135–1175","about 1150":"circa 1150","1154":"1154","1175":"1175","1140":"1140","1150":"1150","1160":"1160","1170":"1170","1181":"1181","1217":"1217","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1125":"1125","1135":"1135","1179":"1179","1200":"1200","1155":"1155","about 1179":"circa 1179","about 1175":"circa 1175","Malpas, Cheshire, England":"Malpas, Cheshire, England"},"en":{"about 1150–":"about 1150–Deceased","1150–Female":"1150–Deceased","1150–Male":"1150–Deceased","1154–Male":"1154–Deceased","1155–Female":"1155–Deceased","1160–Female":"1160–Deceased","1140–1181":"1140–1181","1170–1217":"1170–1217","1175–Male":"1175–Deceased","1179–Male":"1179–Deceased","1125–1200":"1125–1200","1135–1175":"1135–1175","about 1150":"about 1150","1154":"1154","1175":"1175","1140":"1140","1150":"1150","1160":"1160","1170":"1170","1181":"1181","1217":"1217","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1125":"1125","1135":"1135","1179":"1179","1200":"1200","1155":"1155","about 1179":"about 1179","about 1175":"about 1175","Malpas, Cheshire, England":"Malpas, Cheshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"verch","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Otto, Orlo.","German: variant of   Ferch  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Ferch","meanings":["German: variant of   Ferg  . Compare   Verch  .","Probably also an Americanized form of German <b>Förtsch</b> (see   Foertsch  ).","Probably also an Americanized form of German <b>Förch</b> (see   Foerch  )."]}]},{"name":"Ralph","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: from Anglo-Norman and Middle English <i>Raulf</i>, <i>Ralf</i>, an Old French form of ancient Germanic <i>Radulf</i> (from <i>rād</i> ‘counsel, advice’ + <i>wulf</i> ‘wolf’), hence the usual latinization of the name as <i>Radulfus</i>. <i>Ralph</i> was a common personal name among the Normans and from the mid 13th century among the native English. Almost 7% of men in the late 14th century were named <i>Ralph</i>. It was pronounced in a variety of ways, giving rise to a large number of different surnames. <i>Ralf</i> could be shortened to <i>Raff</i>, hence the surname   Raff   and possibly   Raffel  . <i>Raulf</i> was sometimes shortened to <i>Raul</i>, giving us   Rall   and <b>Rawlin</b> (see   Rawling  ). It also appears as <i>Rauf</i>, which was often shortened to <i>Rau</i>, hence the surnames   Rawe   and <b>Rawkin</b> (‘young Ralph’), as well as   Haw  ,   Hawkins  ,   Daw   and   Dawkins  , derived from rhyming pet forms. In late Middle English the diphthong <i>-au-</i> was sometimes simplified to long <i>-a-</i>, later pronounced ‘ay’ as in modern English <i>day</i>, which accounts for <b>Rafe</b>. This pronunciation of the personal name <i>Ralph</i> is still occasionally found in modern times. <i>Ralph</i> is a learned spelling of <i>Ralf</i> that became common in the 16th century. In Anglo-Norman and Middle English usage, the rarer personal name <i>Rolf</i> was sometimes confused with <i>Ralf</i>, which explains why <i>Ralf</i> is an alternative source for   Rolf  ,   Rowe  ,   Dow  , and their derivatives."],"variants":[{"name":"Ralston","meanings":["Scottish: habitational name from Ralston (Renfrewshire), composed of the personal name <i>Raoul</i>, a vernacular form of   Ralph  , + Scots <i>toun</i> ‘farm, village’."]},{"name":"Rao","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Mohan, Krishna, Srinivas, Prakash, Rama, Vijay, Madhu, Ramesh, Ravi, Arun, Bhaskar, Rajesh.","Italian: from a shortened form of the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Radulfo</i>, composed of the elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame, renown’ + <i>wulf</i> ‘wolf’. Compare the English name   Ralph  .","Indian (southern and western states of India and Orissa): name found in several communities, based on Sanskrit <i>rājā</i> ‘king’. The element <i>-rao</i> is freely added to male personal names in certain communities of Maharashtra, Goa, and Andhra Pradesh."]},{"name":"Rull","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Manuel, Rodolfo, Alejandro, Armando, Edmundo, Jaime, Juan.","Catalan: nickname from <i>rull</i>, either in its sense of mill roller, or hair curl.","Catalan: possibly also from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Raülf</i>, composed of the elements <i>rad</i> ‘counsel, advice’ + <i>wolf</i> ‘wolf’. Compare English   Ralph  ."]},{"name":"Rawson","meanings":["English: patronymic meaning ‘son of <i>Rauf</i> or <i>Rau</i>’, Middle English forms of   Ralph   (see   Rawe   3)."]},{"name":"Rau","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Otto, Erwin, Ottmar, Bodo, Frieda, Hans, Reinold, Benno, Bernd, Bernhard, Berthel, Eberhard.","German: nickname for a ruffian, earlier for a hairy person, from Middle High German <i>rūch</i>, <i>rūhe</i>, <i>rouch</i> ‘hairy, shaggy, rough’. This surname is also found in France (Alsace and Lorraine).","English: from a medieval personal name, a variant of   Ralph  ."]},{"name":"Raff","meanings":["German: nickname for a tall thin man, from Middle High German <i>rave</i> ‘lath’.","German: from a personal name, <i>Raffo</i>, as yet unexplained.","English and Scottish: variant of   Ralph  ."]},{"name":"Rall","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt, Erwin, Bernhardt, Dieter, Fritz, Otto, Rainer, Reinhold.","German: nickname for a raucous or noisy individual, from Swabian <i>rallen</i> ‘to make noise, screech like a tomcat’.","English: from the Middle English (from Old French) personal name <i>Raul</i>, a common form of   Ralph  ."]},{"name":"Ralphs","meanings":["English: variant of   Ralph  , with genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."]},{"name":"Rolfe","meanings":["English: of Norman origin, from the Middle English and Anglo-Norman French personal name <i>Rolf</i>, <i>Roulf</i>, <i>Rou</i>, <i>Roul</i>, <i>Rouf</i>, <i>Rof</i>. Its usual derivation is from Old Norse <i>Hrólfr</i>, <i>Rolf</i>, from ancient Germanic <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame, renown’ + <i>wulf</i> ‘wolf’, and occasionally from ancient Germanic <i>Rodulf</i>, of the same origin as <i>Hrólfr</i> (earlier <i>Hróthúlfr</i>) but in a West Frankish form, which the Scandinavian Normans occasionally used. The name was also common in Normandy where it became Old French <i>Roul</i>, <i>Rou</i>, often Latinized as <i>Rollo</i>. See   Ralph   and compare   Rowe  ,   Dow  , and   Rowson  ."]},{"name":"Rawling","meanings":["English: from Middle English <i>Raulin</i>, from an Old French diminutive of <i>Raul</i>, a form of, or corresponding to,   Ralph  , both sometimes used of the same man: for example, Ralph de Knyghton, also called <i>Raulyn</i>, in 1377. Compare   Raw   and   Rawlinson  ."]}]},{"name":"Beannan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Traditional name meaning ‘darling, sweetheart’, also used to denote a fairy lover. This was a common medieval given name, which has enjoyed a revival in recent times."],"variants":[{"name":"Lennan","meanings":["Traditional name meaning ‘darling, sweetheart’, also used to denote a fairy lover. This was a common medieval given name, which has enjoyed a revival in recent times."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":65,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":74,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705189,"age":109,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Beannan verch Ralph of Malpas was born about 1150, in Malpas, Cheshire, England, her father, Ralph ap Eynion of Malpas, was 27 and her mother, Beatrix de Gernon, was 16. She had at least 3 sons with William le Belward. She died in her hometown."},"et":{"about 1150–":"umbes 1150–Surnud","1150–Fema